message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The coracobrachialis muscle is innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which provides sensation to the lateral forearm skin. Therefore, if this nerve is damaged, the patient is most likely to develop a defect in lateral forearm skin sensation. The other options are not innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve.

The coracobrachialis muscle is innervated by the musculocutaneous nerve, which provides cutaneous innervation to the lateral aspect of the forearm. Therefore, if the nerve is damaged, the patient would most likely develop a defect in lateral forearm skin sensation. None of the other options are related to the musculocutaneous nerve or the coracobrachialis muscle.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The coracobrachialis muscle innervates the musculocutaneous nerve, which provides sensory innervation to the lateral forearm skin. Therefore, if the nerve is nicked, the patient would most likely develop a defect in lateral forearm skin sensation. Elbow extension and forearm pronation are controlled by other nerves. Wrist extension is controlled by the radial nerve, which does not innervate the coracobrachialis muscle.
